she:SoilChemicalDegradation a she:Concept ;
  skos:prefLabel "Soil chemical degradation" ;
  skos:definition "Soil chemical degradation is characterised by changes in soil processes, including nutrient depletion, acidification, salinisation and contamination, which in turn leads to a reduced cation exchange capacity, increased aluminium or manganese toxicities, calcium or magnesium deficiencies, and leaching of nitrate nitrogen or other essential plant nutrients. For nutrients and contaminants, annual inputs, such as those from agricultural management (inputs of N, P, K and also copper, zinc, cadmium and antibiotics via animal manure, sewage sludge, compost, digestate or mineral fertilisers) or from additional sources, including inputs via air or sedimentation, are also considered chemical degradation." ;
  she:isCharacterisedBy she:ChangesInSoilProcesses ;
  she:causes she:ReducedCationExchangeCapacity, she:IncreasedAluminiumToxicity, she:IncreasedManganeseToxicity, she:CalciumDeficiency, she:MagnesiumDeficiency, she:LeachingOfNitrateNitrogen, she:LeachingOfEssentialPlantNutrients ;
  she:includes she:AnnualInputsOfNutrientsAndContaminants .

