generated_RDF.text:
The degree of topsoil compaction is difficult to clearly describe with thresholds because conditions are highly unstable and dynamic, for example the negative effects of mechanical seedbed preparation, followed by some recovery after the growing season, the use of cover crops, etc. The degree of topsoil deformation can thus be rather temporary; however, it can also be a warning sign that any continuation of current (harmful) practices is then likely to affect the subsoil. Topsoil compaction is primarily described using the parameters in set I, and can act as a warning sign that current practices do not sufficiently address the sensitivity of the soil. While topsoil compaction can be more easily alleviated, subsoil compaction must be completely avoided. The following section outlines parameters that can be easily measured or which are common in many soil surveys:
•	bulk density, D_b;
•	air capacity, AC;
•	soil texture;
•	visual features of compaction such as platy structure.

